-- #561 (PR-A native #659 + PR-B wasm #661, both SHIPPED — #561 CLOSED) — the
-- GENUINE-VALUE-CYCLE that only LAZINESS can answer, fixed on BOTH backends and
-- serving as a REGRESSION LOCK (acceptance repro #5).
--
-- `x = x + 1` is a non-productive cyclic value: `x` depends on `x`. A topo sort has NO
-- correct order for it (that is why #553 Stage B deliberately left it open). This is the
-- decided intended-abort: eval — the reference engine implementing the DECIDED
-- lazy-nullary semantics — black-holes the cell and raises E-CYCLIC-VALUE (exit 1).
-- #561 makes BOTH backends match: a top-level nullary global reaching a cycle is
-- emitted LAZILY (native: @mdk_force_x + an @mdk_gs_x state flag; wasm: $force_x + a
-- $gs_x state flag — the same 3-state mechanism, see compiler/EAGER-INIT-DESIGN.md
-- §10), and re-entering the still-FORCING cell raises the same coded E-CYCLIC-VALUE,
-- exit 1, EMPTY stdout, on every engine.
--
-- The golden is EMPTY (this harness diffs STDOUT; the error goes to stderr). Before
-- #561 native EAGER-initialised `x`'s cell to 0, computed `0 + 1`, and printed `1` at
-- exit 0 — a silent wrong answer; wasm's pre-#561 ref-mode eager init left the cell
-- null and trapped at instantiate ("dereferencing a null pointer") — the RIGHT exit
-- code for the WRONG reason. If either backend regresses to eager init, this fixture
-- stops raising the coded E-CYCLIC-VALUE and the gate goes red. Do NOT delete it, and
-- do NOT restore the `1` golden.
--
-- The engines ledger row (test/engine_divergence.txt) stays permanently ledgered as
-- `na:eq:na:na:ran:ran` under `eval:intended-abort` — not because anything is still
-- wrong, but because the eval-arm classifier records ANY interpreter E-* runtime error
-- as `na` (arm unavailable) by design (§4.4 of the gate header), so `en`/`ew` can never
-- read `eq` for a fixture whose correct behavior IS an eval-side E-* error. `nw=eq`
-- (native and wasm both empty-stdout/exit-1) is the signal that matters here.
--
-- PR-C added sibling regression coverage for other cycle shapes:
-- eager_global_mutual_cycle.mdk (a two-node mutual cycle) and
-- test/llvm_fixtures_typed/eager_global_dispatch_hidden_cycle.mdk (a cycle whose back
-- edge is hidden behind interface-method dispatch).
--
-- Measured on the shipping engines after #561 (2026-07-18), all three:
--   eval   -> runtime error [E-CYCLIC-VALUE], exit 1, empty stdout   (correct)
--   native -> runtime error [E-CYCLIC-VALUE], exit 1, empty stdout   (FIXED — was `1`)
--   wasm   -> runtime error [E-CYCLIC-VALUE], exit 1, empty stdout   (FIXED — was an
--                                                                     unnamed null-deref trap)

x = x + 1

main = x
